results.overview: At THE MAX, we facilitate teaching and learning practices that enable our scholars to grow as independent learners, think critically, and apply learning to real-world situations. As the largest elementary school in NYC district 9, we provide a holistic educational experience that is difficult to replicate in a public education setting. By incorporating a socially responsive curriculum, we promote rich student discussion while integrating innovative STEM practices. This only happens at THE MAX; where a creative, caring, community nurtures the future innovators of tomorrow.  The Path Program provides support for students who have experienced trauma or stressful events, in an inclusive setting to learn in a district school alongside peers with and without IEPs. Students receive intensive behavioral and social emotional supports in the classroom and throughout the day by trained teachers, social workers and occupational therapists. Students in this program often have or are at risk of an educational classification of emotional disability. For more information, speak with your CSE or IEP team and refer to schools.nyc.gov/SpecializedPrograms. The Intensive Reading Education and Development (IREAD) program is a literacy program, in an integrated co-teaching setting where students receive focused and individualized instruction through a reading intervention that is provided during all subjects to support literacy, language, and speech skills. For more information, speak with your CSE or IEP team and refer to schools.nyc.gov/SpecializedPrograms.

results.overview:
Our Mission:


At P.S. 75, our mission is to provide our children with the necessary skills, knowledge and tools to be creative problem solvers, independent thinkers, and caring and empathetic global citizens.


Our Vision:


P.S. 75 is a community that works together to:

Create a safe, nurturing, and engaging environment.

Strengthen education through respectful and responsive partnerships between home, school, and the broader community.

Develop responsible, competent, and independent students who are lifelong learners and contributing members of society.

Celebrate the diversity of our academic, linguistic, cultural, and socioeconomic backgrounds. This school has ASD Nest: Open to students currently enrolled in the ASD (Autism Spectrum Disorder) Nest program. If you are applying to ASD programs for the first time, please visit www.schools.nyc.gov/specializedprograms for the application and contact ASDprograms@schools.nyc.gov with questions.
